</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Improper positioning of the breasts in a dedicated breast coil causes inhomogeneous fat saturation as well as other artifacts that decrease the sensitivity of breast magnetic resonance imaging. Improper positioning can create artifacts that can obscure a malignancy or cause it to be missed. Goals of proper positioning include imaging the maximum area of breast tissue, minimizing skin folds, and achieving homogeneous fat suppression and nondeformed breast parenchyma. Review of prior images gives the technologist an impression of what the positioning and imaging challenges may be in each patient before the patient enters the imaging unit. Checking the triplane localizer images and repositioning as necessary before any diagnostic or interventional imaging is key. Using a fat saturation pad, changing the arm position, or “rolling” the patient may be considered in difficult cases. Padding to support the patient in an oblique position, using angled sponges to increase breast compression thickness, and raising the grid to access posterior lesions may be helpful in targeting difficult-to-access lesions for biopsy. Using the presented positioning techniques and suggestions, in addition to strict attention to detail before imaging, will improve image quality, decrease imaging time and suboptimal images, and limit the need for repeat imaging studies.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.341125193">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.341125193">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig1a.jpeg" height="651" width="807" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Coil setup. <b>(a)</b> Example of an open coil system. Disposable paper linen protects the coil and is preferable to cloth linen. <b>(b)</b> Example of a closed coil system.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig1b.jpeg" height="651" width="868" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Coil setup. <b>(a)</b> Example of an open coil system. Disposable paper linen protects the coil and is preferable to cloth linen. <b>(b)</b> Example of a closed coil system.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig2.jpeg" height="603" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Guiding the patient into the coil. As the patient positions herself in the coil, the technologist’s hand over the patient’s back guides the patient into the coil while the other hand smooths out inferior breast skin folds by pulling downward toward the patient’s feet (arrow), maintaining tension as the breast drops into the coil.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig3.jpeg" height="756" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> Lateral view shows the breast properly centered in the coil. The patient’s head is toward the right side of the image and the patient’s feet are toward the left side of the image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig4.jpeg" height="598" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Top-down view. View from the top of the coil, from the patient’s head down toward the patient’s feet, shows that the breast is pointing medially (arrow) when viewed from the top down. The breast can appear well positioned from the lateral view but may actually be pointing medially when viewed from the top down.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig5.jpeg" height="603" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> Properly positioned breast from the top-down view. White arrow = medial breast, yellow arrow = lateral breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig6a.jpeg" height="691" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Poor superior positioning. <b>(a)</b> Lateral view shows the breast positioned too far superiorly in the coil with too much inferior abdominal tissue (arrow). The patient’s head is toward the right side of the image and the patient’s feet are toward the left side of the image. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast MR image shows artifact from poor fat saturation (arrow) due to decoupling superiorly. This is a result of positioning too far superiorly in the coil. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal postcontrast MR image, obtained with the breast optimally positioned and centered in the coil, shows homogeneous fat suppression with no decoupling superiorly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig6b.jpeg" height="887" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Poor superior positioning. <b>(a)</b> Lateral view shows the breast positioned too far superiorly in the coil with too much inferior abdominal tissue (arrow). The patient’s head is toward the right side of the image and the patient’s feet are toward the left side of the image. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast MR image shows artifact from poor fat saturation (arrow) due to decoupling superiorly. This is a result of positioning too far superiorly in the coil. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal postcontrast MR image, obtained with the breast optimally positioned and centered in the coil, shows homogeneous fat suppression with no decoupling superiorly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig6c.jpeg" height="887" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Poor superior positioning. <b>(a)</b> Lateral view shows the breast positioned too far superiorly in the coil with too much inferior abdominal tissue (arrow). The patient’s head is toward the right side of the image and the patient’s feet are toward the left side of the image. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast MR image shows artifact from poor fat saturation (arrow) due to decoupling superiorly. This is a result of positioning too far superiorly in the coil. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal postcontrast MR image, obtained with the breast optimally positioned and centered in the coil, shows homogeneous fat suppression with no decoupling superiorly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig7a.jpeg" height="469" width="936" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Poor fat suppression. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image of the bilateral breasts shows poor fat suppression laterally (curved arrows) and medially (straight arrow) as a result of poor positioning. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image, obtained during repeat imaging with the patient centered in the coil, shows homogeneous fat suppression laterally (curved arrows) and medially (straight arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig7b.jpeg" height="469" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Poor fat suppression. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image of the bilateral breasts shows poor fat suppression laterally (curved arrows) and medially (straight arrow) as a result of poor positioning. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image, obtained during repeat imaging with the patient centered in the coil, shows homogeneous fat suppression laterally (curved arrows) and medially (straight arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig8a.jpeg" height="516" width="950" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Skin folds. <b>(a)</b> Axial triplane localizer MR image shows bilateral breast skin folds laterally (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image after repositioning shows resolution of the bilateral breast skin folds laterally (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig8b.jpeg" height="516" width="925" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Skin folds. <b>(a)</b> Axial triplane localizer MR image shows bilateral breast skin folds laterally (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image after repositioning shows resolution of the bilateral breast skin folds laterally (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig9.jpeg" height="1046" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Skin fold. Sagittal triplane localizer MR image shows a skin fold (arrow), which will be present on all subsequent images if the patient is not repositioned.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig10a.jpeg" height="610" width="976" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Large breasts. <b>(a)</b> Axial dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat suppression medially (arrows) in both breasts. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast delayed T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat suppression superiorly (white arrow) and inferiorly (yellow arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows bilateral breast compression anteriorly (arrows) against the coil or “anterior puddling.” This may cause inhomogeneous inflow of contrast material and may obscure a retroareolar malignancy. Positioning may be improved by placing a pad on the coil underneath the patient’s sternum so that the breasts hang freely, resulting in homogeneous fat suppression medially and laterally and resolution of the anterior puddling. <b>(d)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows homogeneous fat suppression bilaterally after placement of a pad underneath the patient’s sternum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig10b.jpeg" height="610" width="598" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Large breasts. <b>(a)</b> Axial dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat suppression medially (arrows) in both breasts. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast delayed T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat suppression superiorly (white arrow) and inferiorly (yellow arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows bilateral breast compression anteriorly (arrows) against the coil or “anterior puddling.” This may cause inhomogeneous inflow of contrast material and may obscure a retroareolar malignancy. Positioning may be improved by placing a pad on the coil underneath the patient’s sternum so that the breasts hang freely, resulting in homogeneous fat suppression medially and laterally and resolution of the anterior puddling. <b>(d)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows homogeneous fat suppression bilaterally after placement of a pad underneath the patient’s sternum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig10c.jpeg" height="615" width="923" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Large breasts. <b>(a)</b> Axial dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat suppression medially (arrows) in both breasts. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast delayed T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat suppression superiorly (white arrow) and inferiorly (yellow arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows bilateral breast compression anteriorly (arrows) against the coil or “anterior puddling.” This may cause inhomogeneous inflow of contrast material and may obscure a retroareolar malignancy. Positioning may be improved by placing a pad on the coil underneath the patient’s sternum so that the breasts hang freely, resulting in homogeneous fat suppression medially and laterally and resolution of the anterior puddling. <b>(d)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows homogeneous fat suppression bilaterally after placement of a pad underneath the patient’s sternum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig10d.jpeg" height="615" width="954" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span> Large breasts. <b>(a)</b> Axial dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat suppression medially (arrows) in both breasts. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast delayed T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat suppression superiorly (white arrow) and inferiorly (yellow arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows bilateral breast compression anteriorly (arrows) against the coil or “anterior puddling.” This may cause inhomogeneous inflow of contrast material and may obscure a retroareolar malignancy. Positioning may be improved by placing a pad on the coil underneath the patient’s sternum so that the breasts hang freely, resulting in homogeneous fat suppression medially and laterally and resolution of the anterior puddling. <b>(d)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows homogeneous fat suppression bilaterally after placement of a pad underneath the patient’s sternum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig11a.jpeg" height="824" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Large breasts that overfill the coil. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal postcontrast delayed T1-weighted MR image shows a breast that is too large for the coil, producing multiple skin folds (arrows) as the breast overfills the coil. As a result of the improper positioning, the breast parenchyma is crowded together and contrast material will not flow evenly into the tissue. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image after repositioning in a larger coil shows smooth skin, absence of skin folds (arrows), and more evenly spread out breast parenchyma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig11b.jpeg" height="824" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Large breasts that overfill the coil. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal postcontrast delayed T1-weighted MR image shows a breast that is too large for the coil, producing multiple skin folds (arrows) as the breast overfills the coil. As a result of the improper positioning, the breast parenchyma is crowded together and contrast material will not flow evenly into the tissue. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image after repositioning in a larger coil shows smooth skin, absence of skin folds (arrows), and more evenly spread out breast parenchyma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig12.jpeg" height="608" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Medial inhomogeneous fat suppression in a patient with large breasts. Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows poor fat saturation medially at the sternum (arrow) from breast tissue pressing directly against the coil due to large patient size. A solution is to use padding to elevate the patient up off the coil medially at the sternum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig13a.jpeg" height="910" width="761" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Inferior bulge. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal triplane localizer image shows an inferior bulge (arrow), which causes inhomogeneous fat suppression inferiorly. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image after repositioning shows resolution of the bulge (arrow). If an inferior bulge is noted on a sagittal triplane localizer image, the solution is to lift and roll the patient, pulling breast tissue up into the coil and abdominal tissue down out of the coil. <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat saturation inferiorly as a result of an inferior bulge. <b>(d)</b> Corresponding image after repositioning with removal of the bulge shows homogeneous fat suppression inferiorly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig13b.jpeg" height="910" width="713" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Inferior bulge. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal triplane localizer image shows an inferior bulge (arrow), which causes inhomogeneous fat suppression inferiorly. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image after repositioning shows resolution of the bulge (arrow). If an inferior bulge is noted on a sagittal triplane localizer image, the solution is to lift and roll the patient, pulling breast tissue up into the coil and abdominal tissue down out of the coil. <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat saturation inferiorly as a result of an inferior bulge. <b>(d)</b> Corresponding image after repositioning with removal of the bulge shows homogeneous fat suppression inferiorly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig13c.jpeg" height="470" width="872" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> Inferior bulge. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal triplane localizer image shows an inferior bulge (arrow), which causes inhomogeneous fat suppression inferiorly. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image after repositioning shows resolution of the bulge (arrow). If an inferior bulge is noted on a sagittal triplane localizer image, the solution is to lift and roll the patient, pulling breast tissue up into the coil and abdominal tissue down out of the coil. <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat saturation inferiorly as a result of an inferior bulge. <b>(d)</b> Corresponding image after repositioning with removal of the bulge shows homogeneous fat suppression inferiorly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig13d.jpeg" height="470" width="1003" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span> Inferior bulge. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal triplane localizer image shows an inferior bulge (arrow), which causes inhomogeneous fat suppression inferiorly. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image after repositioning shows resolution of the bulge (arrow). If an inferior bulge is noted on a sagittal triplane localizer image, the solution is to lift and roll the patient, pulling breast tissue up into the coil and abdominal tissue down out of the coil. <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat saturation inferiorly as a result of an inferior bulge. <b>(d)</b> Corresponding image after repositioning with removal of the bulge shows homogeneous fat suppression inferiorly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig14a.jpeg" height="542" width="936" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Fat saturation pads. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of a fat saturation pad (arrows) that may be used to eliminate the air-tissue interface caused by sharp-angled anatomic structures such as the junction of the breast and chest wall, therefore making fat suppression more homogeneous. <b>(b)</b> Another example of a fat saturation pad.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig14b.jpeg" height="542" width="936" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Fat saturation pads. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of a fat saturation pad (arrows) that may be used to eliminate the air-tissue interface caused by sharp-angled anatomic structures such as the junction of the breast and chest wall, therefore making fat suppression more homogeneous. <b>(b)</b> Another example of a fat saturation pad.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig15a.jpeg" height="629" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Positioning of a fat saturation pad. Lateral views show a balloon model, with the patient’s head toward the right side of the image and the patient’s feet toward the left side of the image. <b>(a)</b> Poor positioning of a fat saturation pad. The pad (white arrows) is placed adjacent to the inferior breast, with the breast positioned too far superiorly in the coil and the the nipple (blue arrow) pointing toward the patient’s head. <b>(b)</b> Proper positioning of a fat saturation pad. The pad (white arrows) is placed against the inferior aspect of the breast, with the breast hanging freely and the nipple (yellow arrow) pointing straight down.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig15b.jpeg" height="629" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Positioning of a fat saturation pad. Lateral views show a balloon model, with the patient’s head toward the right side of the image and the patient’s feet toward the left side of the image. <b>(a)</b> Poor positioning of a fat saturation pad. The pad (white arrows) is placed adjacent to the inferior breast, with the breast positioned too far superiorly in the coil and the the nipple (blue arrow) pointing toward the patient’s head. <b>(b)</b> Proper positioning of a fat saturation pad. The pad (white arrows) is placed against the inferior aspect of the breast, with the breast hanging freely and the nipple (yellow arrow) pointing straight down.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig16a.jpeg" height="876" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Another example of fat saturation pad use. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal postcontrast delayed T1-weighted MR image shows poor fat suppression superiorly (yellow arrow), inferiorly (blue arrow), and posteriorly (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows poor fat suppression posteriorly (arrows). A fat saturation pad can be wrapped around the breast, which will improve the posterior signal. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding MR image obtained by using a fat saturation pad shows homogeneous fat saturation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig16b.jpeg" height="639" width="885" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Another example of fat saturation pad use. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal postcontrast delayed T1-weighted MR image shows poor fat suppression superiorly (yellow arrow), inferiorly (blue arrow), and posteriorly (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows poor fat suppression posteriorly (arrows). A fat saturation pad can be wrapped around the breast, which will improve the posterior signal. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding MR image obtained by using a fat saturation pad shows homogeneous fat saturation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig16c.jpeg" height="639" width="989" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> Another example of fat saturation pad use. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal postcontrast delayed T1-weighted MR image shows poor fat suppression superiorly (yellow arrow), inferiorly (blue arrow), and posteriorly (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows poor fat suppression posteriorly (arrows). A fat saturation pad can be wrapped around the breast, which will improve the posterior signal. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding MR image obtained by using a fat saturation pad shows homogeneous fat saturation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig17a.jpeg" height="772" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Inhomogeneous fat suppression due to lumpectomy and radiation therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows the scar and inhomogeneous fat suppression (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image after placement of a fat saturation pad, which made the scar (arrow) more level, flatter, and less concave, resulting in a better, more homogeneous image. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal triplane localizer image shows the contour of the fat saturation pad (arrow) placed inferiorly against the breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig17b.jpeg" height="760" width="816" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> Inhomogeneous fat suppression due to lumpectomy and radiation therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows the scar and inhomogeneous fat suppression (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image after placement of a fat saturation pad, which made the scar (arrow) more level, flatter, and less concave, resulting in a better, more homogeneous image. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal triplane localizer image shows the contour of the fat saturation pad (arrow) placed inferiorly against the breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig17c.jpeg" height="760" width="760" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span> Inhomogeneous fat suppression due to lumpectomy and radiation therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows the scar and inhomogeneous fat suppression (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image after placement of a fat saturation pad, which made the scar (arrow) more level, flatter, and less concave, resulting in a better, more homogeneous image. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal triplane localizer image shows the contour of the fat saturation pad (arrow) placed inferiorly against the breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig18a.jpeg" height="471" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Silicone implants. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows the implants bulging out to the sides (arrowheads). The patient returned for repeat imaging and was imaged with her arms by her sides; special attention was given to smoothing out the folds, and a fat saturation pad was used. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image from the repeat study shows a more normal appearance of the breast parenchyma around and in front of the implants (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig18b.jpeg" height="471" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Silicone implants. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows the implants bulging out to the sides (arrowheads). The patient returned for repeat imaging and was imaged with her arms by her sides; special attention was given to smoothing out the folds, and a fat saturation pad was used. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding image from the repeat study shows a more normal appearance of the breast parenchyma around and in front of the implants (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig19a.jpeg" height="438" width="876" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Missed cancer due to poor positioning. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat suppression in the right breast (arrow). The patient returned for repeat imaging with a fat saturation pad placed adjacent to the right breast, which resulted in homogeneous fat suppression. <b>(b)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic delayed T1-weighted MR image shows a 1-cm enhancing mass (arrow), which was not initially visible due to poor positioning and subsequent inhomogeneous fat suppression. Pathologic analysis demonstrated invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig19b.jpeg" height="438" width="999" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Missed cancer due to poor positioning. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows inhomogeneous fat suppression in the right breast (arrow). The patient returned for repeat imaging with a fat saturation pad placed adjacent to the right breast, which resulted in homogeneous fat suppression. <b>(b)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic delayed T1-weighted MR image shows a 1-cm enhancing mass (arrow), which was not initially visible due to poor positioning and subsequent inhomogeneous fat suppression. Pathologic analysis demonstrated invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig20a.jpeg" height="392" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> Pseudo cancer due to improper positioning in a 64-year-old asymptomatic woman with a strong family history of breast cancer who underwent screening breast MR imaging. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows asymmetry, with the right breast smaller than the left, and a possible mass laterally (arrow) with associated skin thickening. The patient returned for repeat imaging due to poor positioning. <b>(b)</b> Axial precontrast T1-weighted MR image with the nipples in profile shows normal breast parenchyma bilaterally. The previously seen right lateral abnormality was due to improper positioning of the nipple, which was pressed laterally against the coil.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig20b.jpeg" height="393" width="937" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> Pseudo cancer due to improper positioning in a 64-year-old asymptomatic woman with a strong family history of breast cancer who underwent screening breast MR imaging. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast dynamic T1-weighted MR image shows asymmetry, with the right breast smaller than the left, and a possible mass laterally (arrow) with associated skin thickening. The patient returned for repeat imaging due to poor positioning. <b>(b)</b> Axial precontrast T1-weighted MR image with the nipples in profile shows normal breast parenchyma bilaterally. The previously seen right lateral abnormality was due to improper positioning of the nipple, which was pressed laterally against the coil.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig21a.jpeg" height="602" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span> Padding such as a rolled blanket or towel can be used to support the patient in a prone oblique position, so that more posterior tissue can be accessible for biopsy. <b>(a)</b> Example of rolled blankets to support the patient in a prone oblique position. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a patient in a prone oblique position supported by rolled padding, thereby enabling more posterior tissue to be accessible for biopsy. The patient’s head is toward the right side of the image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig21b.jpeg" height="602" width="807" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span> Padding such as a rolled blanket or towel can be used to support the patient in a prone oblique position, so that more posterior tissue can be accessible for biopsy. <b>(a)</b> Example of rolled blankets to support the patient in a prone oblique position. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a patient in a prone oblique position supported by rolled padding, thereby enabling more posterior tissue to be accessible for biopsy. The patient’s head is toward the right side of the image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig22a.jpeg" height="655" width="952" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span> <b>(a)</b> Sponges. Photograph shows angled (arrow) and rectangular sponges, which may be used to bolster the breast tissue if compression thickness is inadequate, such as in elderly patients with thin breasts, anteriorly adjacent to the nipple or inferiorly. The sponges may increase breast compression thickness, thereby allowing biopsy to be performed safely. <b>(b)</b> Diagram of a top-down view of the breast with a sponge in place shows how sponges may increase anterior compression for biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig22b.jpeg" height="656" width="918" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span> <b>(a)</b> Sponges. Photograph shows angled (arrow) and rectangular sponges, which may be used to bolster the breast tissue if compression thickness is inadequate, such as in elderly patients with thin breasts, anteriorly adjacent to the nipple or inferiorly. The sponges may increase breast compression thickness, thereby allowing biopsy to be performed safely. <b>(b)</b> Diagram of a top-down view of the breast with a sponge in place shows how sponges may increase anterior compression for biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig23a.jpeg" height="589" width="859" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span> Raising the biopsy grid to access posterior lesions. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the MR imaging biopsy grid raised (arrows), which allows biopsy access for more posterior tissue. <b>(b)</b> Photograph shows a different MR imaging biopsy grid, with the lateral coil element moved down to access more posterior tissue for biopsy. The posterior grid row (arrows) is now accessible for biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig23b.jpeg" height="589" width="916" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span> Raising the biopsy grid to access posterior lesions. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the MR imaging biopsy grid raised (arrows), which allows biopsy access for more posterior tissue. <b>(b)</b> Photograph shows a different MR imaging biopsy grid, with the lateral coil element moved down to access more posterior tissue for biopsy. The posterior grid row (arrows) is now accessible for biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig24.jpeg" height="939" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span> MR imaging–guided core biopsy of a far posterior mass. Sagittal postcontrast delayed MR image shows the biopsy obturator (arrow) in the center of an enhancing mass located far posteriorly in the right breast. Biopsy was accomplished by rolling the patient obliquely using padding and raising the grid for more posterior access.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig25a.jpeg" height="545" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig25a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span> Wire localization of an axillary mass in a 66-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy with transverse rectus abdominus myocutaneous (TRAM) flap reconstruction 17 years earlier in whom a left chest wall recurrence was detected. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows a new 4.7-cm enhancing left axillary mass. US and US-guided core biopsy were performed with a pathologic finding of invasive ductal carcinoma, consistent with a left chest wall recurrence. <b>(b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image after neoadjuvant chemotherapy shows decrease in size of the mass (circle) to 1.6 0.7 cm. Preoperative MR imaging–guided wire localization was requested by the surgeon. <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image of the left breast shows an MR imaging–compatible localization wire (arrow) placed through the mass to guide surgical excision. Access was achieved by placing the patient in the prone oblique position supported by padding and with her arm over her head.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig25b.jpeg" height="557" width="958" aria-labelledby="fig25b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span> Wire localization of an axillary mass in a 66-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy with transverse rectus abdominus myocutaneous (TRAM) flap reconstruction 17 years earlier in whom a left chest wall recurrence was detected. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows a new 4.7-cm enhancing left axillary mass. US and US-guided core biopsy were performed with a pathologic finding of invasive ductal carcinoma, consistent with a left chest wall recurrence. <b>(b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image after neoadjuvant chemotherapy shows decrease in size of the mass (circle) to 1.6 0.7 cm. Preoperative MR imaging–guided wire localization was requested by the surgeon. <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image of the left breast shows an MR imaging–compatible localization wire (arrow) placed through the mass to guide surgical excision. Access was achieved by placing the patient in the prone oblique position supported by padding and with her arm over her head.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig25c.jpeg" height="557" width="917" aria-labelledby="fig25c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25c</span> Wire localization of an axillary mass in a 66-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy with transverse rectus abdominus myocutaneous (TRAM) flap reconstruction 17 years earlier in whom a left chest wall recurrence was detected. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows a new 4.7-cm enhancing left axillary mass. US and US-guided core biopsy were performed with a pathologic finding of invasive ductal carcinoma, consistent with a left chest wall recurrence. <b>(b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image after neoadjuvant chemotherapy shows decrease in size of the mass (circle) to 1.6 0.7 cm. Preoperative MR imaging–guided wire localization was requested by the surgeon. <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image of the left breast shows an MR imaging–compatible localization wire (arrow) placed through the mass to guide surgical excision. Access was achieved by placing the patient in the prone oblique position supported by padding and with her arm over her head.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig25c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig26a.jpeg" height="690" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig26a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26a</span> Biopsy of a high-risk screening patient with silicone implants. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows the biopsy target of linear non-masslike enhancement (NMLE) (yellow arrow) in the right breast. The breast is compressed in the MR imaging biopsy grid anteriorly, and the silicone implant (white arrow) is displaced posteriorly. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows the MR imaging biopsy grid (arrows) placed anterior to the implant, with the implant (arrowheads) posterior to the grid and out of the way of the biopsy. The pathologic result was benign columnar alteration with prominent apical snouts and secretions (CAPPS) with microcysts and focal epithelial hyperplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig26a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig26b.jpeg" height="690" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig26b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26b</span> Biopsy of a high-risk screening patient with silicone implants. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows the biopsy target of linear non-masslike enhancement (NMLE) (yellow arrow) in the right breast. The breast is compressed in the MR imaging biopsy grid anteriorly, and the silicone implant (white arrow) is displaced posteriorly. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows the MR imaging biopsy grid (arrows) placed anterior to the implant, with the implant (arrowheads) posterior to the grid and out of the way of the biopsy. The pathologic result was benign columnar alteration with prominent apical snouts and secretions (CAPPS) with microcysts and focal epithelial hyperplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig26b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341125193/asset/images/large/rg.341125193.fig27.jpeg" height="675" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span> Photograph shows a plastic covering placed over the contralateral breast coil during positioning for biopsy. The cover is raised and angled (arrows) so the patient is supported in a prone oblique position for biopsy of a medial lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341125193&amp;id=fig27">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Bassett LW, Farria DM, Bansal S, Farquhar MA, Wilcox PA, Feig SA. Reasons for failure of a mammography unit at clinical image review in the American College of Radiology Mammography Accreditation Program. <em>Radiology</em> 2000;215(3):698–7